### PART III: MODE-SPECIFIC PLAYBOOKS (10 pages)
*"How to operate in each mode, day-by-day"*

#### Mode A: Study Hall Operations

**3.1 When You're In Study Hall**
- Zc < 0.7
- Everyone has clear, independent work
- No urgent decisions pending

**3.2 Daily Rhythm**
```
Monday 9am: Set week's focus
  "This week: Payment gateway. Available async in #payments-thread."

Monday-Friday: Deep work blocks
  - 2-4 hour blocks, notifications OFF
  - Presence signal: "Study Hall mode: [topic]. Back at [time]."

Friday 4pm: Week summary
  "Payment gateway: 80% done. One blocker (API docs unclear). Will finish Monday."
```

**3.3 Interruption Protocol**

**If you NEED someone's attention:**
1. Check: Is it urgent? (Can it wait 2h? If yes, wait.)
2. Post in relevant thread (NOT DM unless private)
3. Use async format: "Question about X: [context]. No rush, respond when you surface."

**If someone interrupts YOU:**
1. Acknowledge: "Saw this. Will respond by [TIME]."
2. Finish your focus block
3. Respond thoughtfully

**3.4 AI Usage in Study Hall**

**âœ… Good uses:**
- Private research conversations (Claude helping you understand OAuth)
- Draft generation (AI writes first pass, you edit)
- Code review (AI spots bugs you might miss)

**âŒ Bad uses:**
- AI generates content you broadcast without review (increases team Zc)
- AI answers team questions (humans lose context)

**Golden Rule:** AI helps YOU work faster. It doesn't broadcast for you.

**Estimate:** 3 pages

---

#### Mode B: GUSH Operations

**3.5 When You Need GUSH**
- Decision required in <5 days
- Discussion has become circular
- Stakeholders aligned on urgency

**3.6 GUSH Scheduling**

**Lead time:** 24-48h minimum
**Frequency:** Max 2 per week (more = you're in wrong mode)

**3.7 The 24h Pre-Work Rule**

**Strict:** If someone hasn't read pre-work, they can't participate.

**How to enforce:**
```
23h before GUSH: "Reply âœ… when you've read the pre-work."

2h before GUSH: Check responses.
  - If <80% confirmed â†’ Postpone
  - No exceptions (even for executives)
```

**Why this matters:** Cold-start GUSH sessions waste 30 min on context-setting.

**3.8 Post-GUSH Protocol**

**Within 2h:** Decision Record posted in #decisions
**Within 24h:** Action items assigned in project tracker
**Within 1 week:** First checkpoint on execution

**Estimate:** 3 pages

---

#### Mode C: BLUES Operations

**3.9 When You MUST Use BLUES**
- Zc â‰¥ 1.0 (mandatory, not optional)
- Team feels overwhelmed
- 3+ people working on loosely coupled problems

**3.10 BLUES Activation**

**Who can call BLUES:** ANYONE (democratic)

**How to activate:**
```
@channel: "BLUES MODE - Zc is 1.3 (red zone). 
Switching to asynchronous rhythm. 
Pulse updates daily at 4pm in #pulse-updates.
GUSH sessions paused unless BEACON."
```

**What happens immediately:**
1. All scheduled meetings canceled (except BEACONs)
2. Slack notifications â†’ Do Not Disturb by default
3. Focus time blocks expanded (4-6h recommended)
4. Daily pulse becomes mandatory

**3.11 Living in BLUES (Day-to-Day)**

**Morning (9am):**
- Check overnight pulses (5 min)
- Identify your focus for today
- Post intent: "Today: [focus area]"

**Afternoon (4pm):**
- Post pulse (use template)
- Check for BEACONs
- Respond to critical async questions only

**Evening:**
- NO work review (protect boundaries)
- Trust system will converge

**3.12 Exiting BLUES**

**Criteria:**
- Zc drops below 0.8 for 3 consecutive days
- Team votes (simple majority)

**How to exit:**
```
@channel: "Zc now 0.7 (green zone). 
Exiting BLUES mode. 
Returning to Study Hall / GUSH as needed."
```

**Estimate:** 4 pages

